'''''True Self''''' is the fourth studio album by the American [[heavy metal music|metal]] band [[SOiL]], first released in the U.S. on May 2, 2006. It is the band's first album with new vocalist [[A.J. Cavalier]], formerly of World In Pain and Diesel Machine; and their last album to feature rhythm guitarist [[Shaun Glass]]. ''True Self'' was leaked onto [[Peer-to-peer file sharing|P2P]] and [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]] sites on March 4, almost two months before its official release. The album sold 4,000 copies in the US during its first week of release.

A [[music video]] was filmed for \Give It Up\" and released shortly before the album.

'''David Lawrence Lipsey, Baron Lipsey''' (born 21 April 1948) is a British journalist and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician.

After attending [[Bryanston School]], Dorset (1962‚Äì67),<ref>[http://www.davidlipsey.co.uk/biography-cv/ Online autobiography]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Lipsey |first1=David |title=In the Corridors of Power: An Autobiography |date=2012 |publisher=Biteback Publishing |location=London |isbn=9781849544290 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HoO1AwAAQBAJ |accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> Lipsey won an Exhibition in [[Politics, Philosophy and Economics]] (PPE) at [[Magdalen College, Oxford]] in 1968 and graduated with a First Class degree, winning the University Gibbs Prize in Politics in 1969. He went on to become a political adviser to [[Anthony Crosland]] in Opposition and an adviser to 10 Downing Street. He has worked as a journalist for a variety of different publications including the [[Sunday Times]], [[Sunday Correspondent]], [[The Times]], [[The Guardian]] and [[The Economist]]. From 1982 to 1983 he was Chairman of the [[Fabian Society]] and from 1970 to 1972 Secretary of the Streatham Labour Party.

David Lipsey was awarded a Special [[Orwell Prize]] in 1997 for his work as ‚ÄòBagehot‚Äô in The Economist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theorwellprize.co.uk/?s=lipsey|title=Lord Lipsey ‚Äì The Orwell Prize|last=|first=|date=|website=www.theorwellprize.co.uk|publisher=|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>

Lipsey has held numerous senior posts in public life. As well as his economic and social interests, he chairs the All Party Parliamentary group on Classical Music (from 2011), is a patron of the Glasbury Arts Festival, a trustee of the Cambrian Orchestra Trust and chairman of the [[Sidney Nolan|Sidney Nolan Trust]] (from 2011), as well as being a trustee of other arts organisations.<ref name=\:0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-lipsey/2492|title=Lord Lipsey|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref> Lipsey was created a [[Life peer]] as '''Baron Lipsey'''
column5: of [[Tooting Bec]] in the [[London Borough of Wandsworth]]
column6: on 30 July 1999.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55572 |date=4 August 1999 |page=8409}}</ref> He sits on the Labour benches in the House of Lords.

column1: His sporting interests have included harness racing and presidency of the British Harness Racing Club (2008 to 2016) as well as chairmanship of the British Greyhound Racing Board (now the [[Greyhound Board of Great Britain]]) from 2004 to 2009.<ref name=\":0\" />

{{Other uses}}
'''Seven minutes in heaven''' (also known as '''two''', '''five''', '''seven''', or '''ten minutes in the closet''', etc.) is a [[kissing game|kissing]] [[party game]] played at teenage parties.

==The game==
Two people are selected to go into a closet or other dark enclosed space and do whatever they like for seven minutes. It is common for the participants to [[kiss]] or [[Making out|make out]], but they may instead choose to talk, engage in some other (usually quiet) activity, or simply do nothing at all and wait for the time to expire. 

The participants can be selected by various methods, such as [[Spin the bottle|spinning a bottle]], drawing lots or votes.

==History ==
The game has been recorded as early as 1953.<ref name=jet>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mkIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA22 |title=New Game Called '7 Minutes in Heaven' |magazine=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |date=6 August 1953 |page=22}}</ref>

'''Seven minutes in heaven''' (also known as '''two''', '''five''', '''seven''', or '''ten minutes in the closet''', etc.) is a [[kissing game|kissing]] [[party game]] played at teenage parties.

==The game==
Two people are selected to go into a closet or other dark enclosed space and do whatever they like for seven minutes. It is common for the participants to [[kiss]] or [[Making out|make out]], but they may instead choose to talk, engage in some other (usually quiet) activity, or simply do nothing at all and wait for the time to expire. 

The participants can be selected by various methods, such as [[Spin the bottle|spinning a bottle]], drawing lots or votes.

The '''Australian Egg Corporation Limited''' ('''AECL''') is the major marketer of [[egg (food)|eggs]] in Australia.  It is a producer-owned corporation, representing approximately 400 commercial egg producers and is based in [[Sydney]]. The activities of  AECL include [[marketing]], [[research and development]], and policy services.  According to its website, it runs public awareness campaigns on [[animal welfare]], [[nutrition]], and [[vaccine]] development.<ref>[https://www.australianeggs.org.au/ Australian Egg Corporation Limited Website]</ref> However, it has received criticism from animal welfare organisations for using these terms for promotional purposes.<ref>[http://www.animalsaustralia.org/take_action/forgotten-battery-hens Hens abandoned in mega factory farm]</ref> The corporation is affiliated with the [[International Egg Commission]] (IEC).

The AECL was created by an act of [[Parliament of Australia|federal parliament]] in 2002 as a [[statutory authority]] to replace the [[Rural Industries Research and Development Corporation]], as the peak egg body in the country.

In September 2004, the corporation hosted the Annual Conference of the IEC in Sydney. It was awarded the International body's most prestigious prize, the Golden Egg Award. At the same presentation night, the Australian egg industry was judged as the best in the world by an international judging panel.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}

In July 2005, the corporation funded a trip for Brian Spotts of Colorado, to break the world record of standing eggs on end. {{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}

In 2013, consumer rights organisation [[Choice (Australian consumer organisation)|Choice]] made a super-complaint against the AECL after it proposed to change the definition for [[free range eggs]] in Australia from 2000 hens per hectare to 10000 hens per hectare.<ref>[http://www.choice.com.au/media-and-news/media-releases/2013-media-releases/choice-makes-free-range-super-complaint.aspx CHOICE makes free-range super-complaint]</ref> In 2014, the AECL was fined $30000 for faking an egg shortage during an oversupply to boost their profits.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/environment/animals/egg-producers-sought-to-cull-chickens-and-destroy-eggs-in-bid-to-raise-prices-accc-20140528-393uv.html Egg producers sought to cull chickens and destroy eggs in bid to raise prices: ACCC]</ref>

The AECL was created by an act of [[Parliament of Australia|federal parliament]] in 2002 as a [[statute|statutory]] [[authority]] to replace the [[Rural Industries Research and Development Corporation]], as the peak egg body in the country.

In September 2004, the corporation hosted the Annual Conference of the IEC in Sydney. It was awarded the International body's most prestigious prize, the Golden Egg Award. At the same presentation night, the Australian egg industry was judged as the best in the world by an international judging panel.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}

In July 2005, the corporation funded a trip for Brian Spotts of Colorado, to break the world record of standing eggs on end. {{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}

In 2013, consumer rights organisation [[Choice (Australian consumer organisation)|Choice]] made a super-complaint against the AECL after it proposed to change the definition for [[free range eggs]] in Australia from 2000 hens per hectare to 10000 hens per hectare.<ref>[http://www.choice.com.au/media-and-news/media-releases/2013-media-releases/choice-makes-free-range-super-complaint.aspx CHOICE makes free-range super-complaint]</ref> In 2014, the AECL was fined $30000 for faking an egg shortage during an oversupply to boost their profits.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/environment/animals/egg-producers-sought-to-cull-chickens-and-destroy-eggs-in-bid-to-raise-prices-accc-20140528-393uv.html Egg producers sought to cull chickens and destroy eggs in bid to raise prices: ACCC]</ref>

'''Danny O'Brien''' (born 1969) is a British [[technology]] [[journalist]] and civil liberties activist. He is the International Director of the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]].

==Career==
He wrote weekly columns for the ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|Sunday Times]]'' and the ''[[Irish Times]]''; and before that for ''[[The Guardian]]'', and acted as a consultant in helping ''The Guardian'' formulate its online strategy. He worked for the UK edition of ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', as well as for [[Channel 4]] and the British [[Internet Service Provider|ISP]] [[Virgin.net]]. Together with [[Dave Green (journalist)|Dave Green]], he founded and wrote the now-defunct email newsletter ''[[Need To Know (newsletter)|Need To Know]]''.

In May 2005, he succeeded Ren Bucholz as Activist Coordinator for the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], and then became EFF's International Outreach Coordinator. In April 2010, he moved to a new position as Internet Advocacy Coordinator for the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]]. In February 2013, he became the Director of the International Department at the Electronic Frontier Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Danny O'Brien Returns to Head EFF's International Team|url=https://www.eff.org/press/releases/danny-obrien-returns-head-effs-international-team|work=EFF|accessdate=5 May 2014|date=21 February 2013}}</ref>

[[Image:Discussing Fluid Lobbying at Wikimania 2014 - 14682390787.jpg|thumb|Danny O'Brien (on right) in 2014 at [[Wikimania]] ]]
O'Brien also set up a pledge on [[PledgeBank]] to help coordinate the establishment of \an organisation that will campaign for digital rights in the UK\"
column5: which led to the creation of the [[Open Rights Group]].<ref>{{cite web|title=UK digital rights group sets up|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4225938.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=5 May 2014}}</ref>

'''''True Self''''' is the fourth studio album by the [[Chicago]] metal band [[SOiL]]. It was released in the US on May 2, 2006, via [[DRT Entertainment]]. This is the band's first album with new vocalist [[AJ Cavalier]], formerly of World In Pain and Diesel Machine; and their last album to feature rhythm guitarist [[Shaun Glass]]. ''True Self'' was leaked onto [[Peer-to-peer file sharing|P2P]] and [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]] sites on March 4, almost two months before its official release. The album sold 4,000 copies in the US during its first week of release.

A [[music video]] was filmed for \Give It Up\" and released shortly before the album.

[[File:Benjamin_Britten,_London_Records_1968_publicity_photo_for_Wikipedia.jpg|thumb|The composer]]
'''''Cantata misericordium''''', [[opus number|op.]] 69, is a 1963 musical composition by British composer [[Benjamin Britten]]. Its single movement is based on the [[parable of the Good Samaritan]] and was composed for the centenary of the [[Red Cross]].

==History and text==
This [[cantata]] was composed in 1963 for the centenary of the [[Red Cross]].<ref name=em>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/notes_other/n_britten_cantata_misericordium.htm|publisher=Emmanuel Music|title=Benjamin Britten ''Cantata misericordium''|author=Bloch, Gregory|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref>

The [[Latin]] text by Patrick Wilkinson recounts the Biblical [[parable of the Good Samaritan]].<ref name=em/> Because the work was to be premiered at an international event, Britten felt that Latin would be the most appropriate language. He had originally intended to use either the Biblical text or a medieval adaptation, but the International Committee of the Red Cross objected that explicitly religious text would be inappropriate to celebrate an organization with a firm nonsectarian stance.<ref name=em/> To resolve this issue, Britten approached Wilkinson, a Latin professor at [[Cambridge University]], to create a [[libretto]] for the work. '''''Cantata misericordium''''', [[opus number|op.]] 69, is a 1963 musical composition by British composer [[Benjamin Britten]]. Its single movement is based on the [[parable of the Good Samaritan]] and was composed for the centenary of the [[Red Cross]].

==History and text==
This [[cantata]] was composed in 1963 for the centenary of the [[Red Cross]].<ref name=em>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/notes_other/n_britten_cantata_misericordium.htm|publisher=Emmanuel Music|title=Benjamin Britten ''Cantata misericordium''|author=Bloch, Gregory|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref>

The [[Latin]] text by [[Patrick Wilkinson]] recounts the Biblical [[parable of the Good Samaritan]].<ref name=em/> Because the work was to be premiered at an international event, Britten felt that Latin would be the most appropriate language. He had originally intended to use either the Biblical text or a medieval adaptation, but the International Committee of the Red Cross objected that explicitly religious text would be inappropriate to celebrate an organization with a firm nonsectarian stance.<ref name=em/> To resolve this issue, Britten approached Wilkinson, a Latin professor at [[Cambridge University]], to create a [[libretto]] for the work. The resulting text is \somewhat 'academic' and lacking in obviously expressive poetic qualities\" but is notable for its \"recondite

'''''True Self''''' is the fourth studio album by the [[Chicago]] metal band [[SOiL]]. It was released in the US on May 2, 2006, via [[DRT Entertainment]]. This is the band's first album with new vocalist [[AJ Cavalier]], formerly of World In Pain and Diesel Machine; and their last album to feature rhythm guitarist [[Shaun Glass]]. ''True Self'' was leaked onto [[Peer-to-peer file sharing|P2P]] and [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]] sites on March 4, almost two months before its official release. The album sold 4,000 copies in the US during its first week of release.

A [[music video]] was filmed for \Give It Up\" and released shortly before the album.

The '''Municipality of Ru≈°e''' ({{IPA-sl|Àà…æuÀê É…õ|pron|Sl-Ruse.oga}}; {{lang-sl|Obƒçina Ru≈°e}}) is a [[Municipalities of Slovenia|municipality]] in northeastern [[Slovenia]]. The seat of the municipality is the town of [[Ru≈°e]]. It lies on the right bank of the [[Drava|Drava River]] west of [[Maribor]] and extends south into the [[Pohorje]] Hills. The area is part of the traditional region of [[Lower Styria|Styria]]. It is now included in the [[Drava Statistical Region]].<ref>[http://www.ruse.si/ Municipality of Ru≈°e website]</ref>

==Settlements==
In addition to the municipal seat of Ru≈°e, the municipality also includes the following settlements:
{{Div col|colwidth=14em}}
* [[Bezena]]
* [[Bistrica ob Dravi]]
* [[Fala, Ru≈°e|Fala]]
* [[Lobnica, Ru≈°e|Lobnica]]
* [[Log, Ru≈°e|Log]]
* [[Smolnik, Ru≈°e|Smolnik]]
{{Div col end}}

'''Banjariya''' is a [[town]] and [[Village Development Committee (Nepal)|Village Development Committee]]  in [[Bara District]] in the [[Narayani Zone]] of south-eastern [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[2011 Nepal census]] it had a population of 5,999 persons residing in 835 individual households. There were 3,020 males and 2,979 females at the time of census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1 |title=Nepal Census 2001 |work=Nepal's Village Development Committees |publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]] |accessdate=September 18, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012163506/http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1 |archivedate=12 October 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

column3: and hosted the syndicated radio show ''[[Retro Rewind]]'' in 1999. Harris created ''Retro Rewind'' in October 1997. In 1998 Harris briefly took a leave of absence from ''Retro Rewind'' to manage the band [[The Outfield]].<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6150467/john-spinks-guitarist-songwriter-the-outfield-dead-60 Billboard]</ref><ref>[http://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2014/07/john_spinks_dead_the_outfield_your_love_guitarist_dies_cancer.html Syracuse.com]</ref>

column2: having penned a Top 20 hit on the ''[[Billboard magazine]]'' adult contemporary charts in April 2005 called \"[[Sunset Blvd (song)|Sunset Blvd]]\".<ref name=AM>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/livin-on-the-run-mw0000699717 AllMusic]</ref>

column1: Harris has also lent his songwriting talent to others. He has co-written songs with the likes of [[Rob Thomas (musician)|Rob Thomas]]
column4: <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.julianlennon.com/collaborations/ |title=Collaborations - Julian Lennon}}</ref> [[Michael J. Willett]]

column2: Harris formed The Dave Harris Project (featuring [[Michael J. Willett]] on vocals) which released the album ''[[Grandiose Delusions]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thefaulknerreview.wordpress.com/2015/03/29/album-review-grandiose-delusions-by-the-dave-harris-project/ |title=ALBUM REVIEW: Grandiose Delusions by The Dave Harris Project |last=Faulkner |first=Alex |website=The Faulkner Review}}</ref>

column1: In January 2017 Harris was charged with 27 felony counts involving statutory rape and especially aggravated sexual exploitation of a minor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wgnsradio.com/45-year-old-man-accused-of-especially-aggravated-sexual-exploitation-of-a-minor-13-times-cms-37363|title=WGNS News Radio|last=|first=|date=2017-01-23|work=|newspaper=Murfreesboro News and Radio|access-date=2017-01-28|via=}}</ref> He was convicted of those charges in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lebanondemocrat.com/Courts/2018/04/11/Harris-pleads-guilty-to-child-rape.html|title=Harris pleads guilty to child rape|last=Smith|first=Jacob|date=April 11

The '''F/V ''Maverick''''' is a commercial crab fishing vessel that featured on the first three seasons of the [[Discovery Channel]]'s reality television show [[Deadliest Catch]]. The  F/V ''Maverick'' was built by Giddings Boat Works in 1982. She is a 92-foot house aft vessel that holds 120 pots and sleeps between nine and ten people. She was purchased by Rick and Donna Quashnick of [[Warrenton, Oregon]] in 1991. The F/V Maverick was selected for a camera crew for season one in the 2005 opilio crab season, as partner vessel of the [[FV Cornelia Marie|''F/V Cornelia Marie'']]. The ''Maverick'' took part in the rescue efforts for the [[FV Big Valley|''F/V Big Valley'']], which sunk on the first day of the opilio crab season off [[Saint Paul Island (Alaska)|Saint Paul Island, Alaska]] losing all but one crew member. She became a featured vessel beginning in the second and third season of [[Deadliest Catch]], joining the [[FV Cornelia Marie|''F/V Cornelia Marie'']], [[FV Northwestern|''F/V Northwestern'']] and [[FV Time Bandit|''F/V Time Bandit'']].

==Current status==

While the F/V Maverick is no longer on [[Deadliest Catch]], she is still fishing with owners Rick and Donna Quashnick. The F/V Maverick's homeport is [[Astoria, Oregon]]. As shown in the third season of [[Deadliest Catch]], Captain Rick gave control of the ''Maverick'' to the late Blake Painter for the 2006 king crab season. After the 2006 king crab season was over, Painter gave the ''Maverick'' back to Rick and Donna Quashnick.

==Specifications==

*Year of Construction: 1982
*Engine: Diesel
*Hull Construction: Steel
*Length: 92.7‚Ä≤
*Breadth: 24.0‚Ä≤
*Depth: 7.6‚Ä≤
*Gross Tonnage: 173
*Net Tonnage: 148
*Built in 1982 at the Giddings Boat Works in [[Coos Bay, Oregon]]

==See also==
*[[Alaskan king crab fishing]]

==External links==
*[http://dsc.discovery.com/tv-shows/deadliest-catch Deadliest Catch website]

column5: Mardan]] area and also acts as key stream for agriculture across the city.

'''Juan Felipe Gomez (born June 7, 1977)''' is a retired Colombian racquetball player. Gomez won gold at the 1995 South American Games in Men‚Äôs Singles. He was ranked Colombian #1 player for almost a decade, from 1992 to 2002. Gomez was also Junior National Champion and doubles National Champion representing Colombia in various IRF - International Racquetball Federation events such as South America and Pan American Games and World Racquetball Championships.

'''Rachael Laws''' (born 5 November 1990) is an English [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[FA Women's Super League|FA WSL]] side [[Reading F.C. Women|Reading]].

==Playing career==
===Club===
Laws first played for [[Liverpool F.C. Women|Liverpool]] during the [[2013 FA WSL|2013 FA WSL season]]. She played 9 games and helped her side win the title while battling for a place in the first team with Sarah Quantrill.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rachael Laws at Soccerway|url=https://www.soccerway.com/players/rachael-laws/298975/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=20 Feb 2019}}</ref> She then signed for Sunderland on 31 December 2013 going on to make 36 appearances in the WSL. Following [[Sunderland A.F.C. Ladies|Sunderland's]] denial for a place in the [[2018‚Äì19 FA WSL]] she joined [[Reading F.C. Women|Reading]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sunderland Ladies demoted two divisions after losing FA appeal|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/sunderland-ladies-demoted-two-divisions-after-losing-fa-appeal-1-9265420|publisher=Sunderland Echo|date=23 July 2018|accessdate=20 Feb 2019}}</ref> She said in an interview with BBC Sport: \Reading is somewhere I want to personally be and thrive hopefully while I am here\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Reading Women sign goalkeeper Rachael Laws
column5: while Remi Allen signs new deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44681154|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=20 Feb 2019}}</ref>

column1: Laws was called up by [[Mark Sampson]] in 2014 for [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification ‚Äì UEFA Group 6|England's World Cup qualification]] but was an unused substitute in a 10-0 away win against [[Montenegro women's national football team|Montenegro]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=England Women thrash Montenegro 10‚Äì0 in qualifier|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29208334|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 September 2014|accessdate=20 Feb 2019}}</ref>

'''C√©dric Ido''' (born 22 October 1980) is a French-Burkinabe director, writer and actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inside.uncc.edu/news-features/2018-03-30/filmmaker-serve-2018-africana-artist-residence|title=Filmmaker to serve as 2018 Africana Artist-in-Residence|work=UNC Charlotte|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref> He grew up in [[Stains, Seine-Saint-Denis]], a small suburban town near [[Paris]] and in [[Ouagadougou]], [[Burkina Faso]] during [[Thomas Sankara]]‚Äôs revolution. His directing works have been exhibited worldwide in [[film]] festivals such as Seattle, Dubai and Venice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://africultures.com/films/?no=16361|title=Twaaga (Invincible)|work=Africultures|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>

In 2015 he won the [[African Movie Academy Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmcontact.com/news/south-africa/film-festivals/africa-movie-academy-awards-winners-2015|title=The Africa Movie Academy Awards Winners 2015 |work=Film Contact |accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> for best short film with Twaaga,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2012/05/africa-first-2012-profile-burkinabe-filmmaker-cedric-ido-and-his-superhero-cinema-dreams-145439/|title=Africa First 2012 Profile: Burkinab√© Filmmaker Cedric Ido And His Superhero Cinema Dreams|author=Tambay Obenson|work=IndieWire|accessdate=21 May 2012}}</ref> which takes place in Burkina Faso during Thomas Sankara's revolution. He has directed his brother, actor [[Jacky Ido]], on a number of films including Chateau,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shadowandact.com/cannes-cedric-ido-modi-barry-team-up-for-dramedy-chateau-set-in-paris-african-community-rarely-humanized-on-screen/|title=Cannes: C√©dric Ido, Modi Barry Team Up for Dramedy, 'Chateau' - Set in Paris African Community Rarely Humanized on Screen|author=Tambay Obenson|work=Shadow & Act|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/cannes/mk2-films-boards-barry-and-idos-comedy-chateau/5104150.article|title=MK2 Films boards Barry and Ido‚Äôs comedy 'Chateau'|author=Melanie Goodfellow|work=Screen Daily|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> and [[Hasaki Ya Suda]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.unifrance.org/movie/32853/hasaki-ya-suda|title=Hasaki Ya Suda|work=Unifrance|accessdate=5 February 2011}}</ref>
